::overloading_01::Which statement best defines overloading in Java? {
=Overloading defines multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists.
~A reference chain is a sequence of object references used to reach nested data.
~this refers to the current object instance inside an instance method or constructor.
~Object creation in Java is the process of allocating and initializing class instances.
}

::overloading_02::Which Java construct is most directly tied to overloading? {
~Core language features, OOP, collections, exceptions, and tooling are essential proficiency areas.
=Java resolves overloaded methods at compile time using argument types.
~Setter methods and mutating collection operations are common modification mechanisms.
~Assignment operator = copies references for object types.
}

::overloading_03::Which example best demonstrates overloading in Java code? {
~A proficient developer can read stack traces and locate root causes efficiently.
~int count = 0; is valid Java variable syntax.
=println(int) and println(String) are classic overloading examples.
~int, boolean, and double are primitive type examples.
}

::overloading_04::Which is a common mistake when working with overloading? {
~A common mistake is using == instead of equals() for value comparison.
~A common mistake is assuming reference assignment duplicates object contents.
=A common mistake is creating ambiguous overloads that confuse call sites.
~A common mistake is memorizing syntax without understanding object semantics.
}

::overloading_05::Which test most directly validates overloading behavior? {
~A good command test verifies receiver state changes after execute().
=Tests should cover each overloaded signature explicitly.
~A good test distinguishes identity checks from equality checks.
~A good test verifies both side effects and returned output of method calls.
}

::overloading_06::Which performance/maintainability statement about overloading is most accurate? {
~Identity matters for caching, synchronization, and aliasing behavior.
~Excessive nested calls can reduce readability and debugging clarity.
~Consistent variable syntax conventions improve code readability.
=Too many overloads can hurt readability more than they help convenience.
}

::overloading_07::Which refactoring most improves code related to overloading? {
~Refactoring names to reflect role (id, count, customer) improves semantic clarity.
~Refactoring equals/hashCode implementations clarifies value semantics vs identity.
~Refactoring to generics improves type safety and reduces casts.
=Refactoring to distinct method names can improve API clarity.
}

::overloading_08::Which Java API/keyword detail is most relevant to overloading? {
~The compiler performs static type checking on Java code.
~Dependency injection frameworks centralize object creation in larger systems.
=Return type alone cannot differentiate overloaded methods in Java.
~record types provide concise syntax for immutable compound data carriers.
}

::overloading_09::Which debugging approach is most useful for overloading problems? {
~Debuggers are useful for inspecting object graphs and nested field values.
=Compiler error messages are useful when diagnosing overload resolution failures.
~Type mismatch compiler errors are key debugging signals.
~Constructor bugs are often found by checking object state immediately after instantiation.
}

::overloading_10::Which statement about overloading is true? {
~Using new correctly is foundational to Java object lifecycle reasoning.
~Constructors should establish valid invariants before methods are called.
~Understanding reference copying is central to reasoning about Java object mutation.
=Good overloading keeps method meaning consistent across variants.
}
